# CSS Full Border Rule - No border-left

## 🚫 Prohibited Pattern
**NEVER use `border-left` for styling or highlighting**

```css
/* ❌ WRONG: Left-only border */
.card {
    border-left: 4px solid #4caf50;
}

.metric-item {
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent-color);
}
```

## ✅ Required Pattern
**ALWAYS use full borders (all sides)**

```css
/* ✅ CORRECT: Full border */
.card {
    border: 2px solid #4caf50;
    border-radius: 10px;
}

.metric-item {
    border: 2px solid var(--accent-color);
    border-radius: 10px;
}
```

## 🎯 Rationale
- **Professional appearance**: Full borders look more polished and complete
- **Consistency**: All components use the same border pattern
- **Accessibility**: Clear visual boundaries improve readability
- **Design coherence**: Unified styling across the application

## 📐 Border Implementation Standards

### Standard Border Widths
- Thin borders: `1px solid`
- Medium borders: `2px solid`
- Thick borders: `3px solid` (use sparingly)

### Border Radius Guidelines
- Small components: `10px`
- Medium components: `20px`
- Large components: `30px`

### Color Usage
- Use CSS variables for consistency:
  - `var(--border-primary)` for default borders
  - `var(--border-secondary)` for nested elements
  - Specific colors for status indicators (green, red, orange, blue)

## 🔄 Migration Pattern
When refactoring existing code:

```css
/* Before (incorrect) */
.element {
    border-left: 4px solid #4caf50;
    padding: 8px 14px;
}

/* After (correct) */
.element {
    border: 2px solid #4caf50;
    border-radius: 10px;
    padding: 10px;
}
```

## ⚠️ Exceptions
There are NO exceptions to this rule in the HealthMetric project. All borders must be full borders on all sides.
